Gemini: The MOST EFFECTIVE NEXT STEP to diagnose the deployment failure is to CHECK the VERTEX AI DEPLOYMENT LOGS in the GOOGLE CLOUD CONSOLE.

You previously provided excellent notes on "How to Retrieve Vertex AI Debugging Logs." Let's utilize those instructions IMMEDIATELY to pinpoint the deployment error.

ACTION 1.6.8: RETRIEVE VERTEX AI DEPLOYMENT LOGS via GOOGLE CLOUD CONSOLE (GUI):

Please follow these STEP-BY-STEP INSTRUCTIONS to retrieve the VERTEX AI DEPLOYMENT LOGS using the GOOGLE CLOUD CONSOLE (GUI):

(Referring to your "📌 How to Retrieve Vertex AI Debugging Logs" notes):

STEP 1: GO TO GOOGLE CLOUD CONSOLE:

Open your web browser and navigate to the Google Cloud Console: https://console.cloud.google.com/
Ensure you are logged in with the CORRECT GOOGLE CLOUD ACCOUNT and that your PROJECT is selected (ai-execution-system).
STEP 2: NAVIGATE to LOGS EXPLORER:

In the Google Cloud Console left-hand navigation menu, find "Logging" and click on it to expand the Logging section.
Then, click on "Logs Explorer." This will open the Logs Explorer interface.
STEP 3: ENTER LOG QUERY in QUERY BUILDER:

In the "Query Builder" section at the top of the Logs Explorer page, COPY and PASTE the following FILTER QUERY EXACTLY as shown below:

resource.type="aiplatform.googleapis.com/Model"
logName:"projects/YOUR_PROJECT_ID/logs/aiplatform.googleapis.com%2FmodelDeployment"
IMPORTANT: REPLACE YOUR_PROJECT_ID in the query above with your ACTUAL Google Cloud PROJECT ID (ai-execution-system).

DOUBLE-CHECK that you have pasted the query correctly and replaced YOUR_PROJECT_ID.

STEP 4: RUN QUERY and EXAMINE LOGS:

Click the "Run Query" button in the Logs Explorer.
EXAMINE the LOG ENTRIES that are displayed in the "Query Results" pane below.
Specifically, LOOK for LOG ENTRIES that have a SEVERITY LEVEL of "ERROR" or "CRITICAL". These error logs will contain details about why the model deployment failed.
CAREFULLY READ the ERROR MESSAGES in the log entries. Look for keywords or phrases that indicate the ROOT CAUSE of the deployment failure. Common error categories to look for based on your previous debugging notes and experience include:
PERMISSION DENIED errors: Indicate IAM permission issues (e.g., Vertex AI Service Agent lacking required permissions).
CONTAINER IMAGE errors: Issues with pulling or accessing the Docker container image (e.g., image not found, invalid image path, Docker errors).
CONFIGURATION ERRORS: Errors related to model configuration settings (e.g., hyperparameter errors, invalid model parameters - like the whitespace issue you encountered before, although this might be a different error now).
INFRASTRUCTURE ERRORS: Less common, but could indicate issues with Vertex AI infrastructure or resource availability in the selected region.
STEP 5: REPORT BACK LOG FINDINGS:

Once you have reviewed the Vertex AI Deployment Logs and identified any ERROR MESSAGES, PLEASE REPORT BACK to me with the following information:
What SPECIFIC ERROR MESSAGES did you find in the logs? Please COPY and PASTE the FULL ERROR MESSAGE TEXT if possible.
Based on the error messages, what do you think is the ROOT CAUSE of the deployment failure? (e.g., Permission error, Container Image error, Configuration error, etc.)
If you are unsure about the root cause, please provide the FULL ERROR LOG TEXT, and I will help you analyze it.
Jesse, retrieving and analyzing the Vertex AI Deployment Logs is the MOST DIRECT PATH to understanding why your model deployment failed. Please follow these GUI instructions to access the logs and report back your findings. Let's pinpoint the error and get this deployment back on track!
